<span id="freeTextContainer16117230313702343613">Allllllll the history this time, and the focus is not really on the murder of Hugh Beringar’s boss when he has just arrived home as part of a prisoner exchange (whoohoo all the historical fact again, without being dry and know-it-all-y ala Sister Fidelma) but instead on battles, raids, and our usual young lovers. One star knocked off because I was slightly shocked by the lenient attitude taken by Brother Cadfael towards the murderer but I suppose that’s part of how human Cadfael is compared to t</span>
  <span id="freeText16117230313702343613" style="display:none">Allllllll the history this time, and the focus is not really on the murder of Hugh Beringar’s boss when he has just arrived home as part of a prisoner exchange (whoohoo all the historical fact again, without being dry and know-it-all-y ala Sister Fidelma) but instead on battles, raids, and our usual young lovers. One star knocked off because I was slightly shocked by the lenient attitude taken by Brother Cadfael towards the murderer but I suppose that’s part of how human Cadfael is compared to the majority of the medieval sleuths. Really, Pargeter’s history here is as good as her less fictional works published without her pseudonym.</span>
